Credit Card Users Churn Prediction¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers’ leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same – so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Data Description¶

  • CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
  • Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then "Attrited Customer" else "Existing Customer"
  • Customer_Age: Age in Years
  • Gender: Gender of the account holder
  • Dependent_count: Number of dependents
  • Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder - Graduate, High School, Unknown, Uneducated, College(refers to college student), Post-Graduate, Doctorate
  • Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder
  • Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder
  • Card_Category: Type of Card
  • Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank (in months)
  • Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
  • Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
  • Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Average Card Utilization Ratio

What Is a Revolving Balance?¶

  • If we don't pay the balance of the revolving credit account in full every month, the unpaid portion carries over to the next month. That's called a revolving balance
What is the Average Open to buy?¶
  • 'Open to Buy' means the amount left on your credit card to use. Now, this column represents the average of this value for the last 12 months.
What is the Average utilization Ratio?¶
  • The Avg_Utilization_Ratio represents how much of the available credit the customer spent. This is useful for calculating credit scores.
Relation b/w Avg_Open_To_Buy, Credit_Limit and Avg_Utilization_Ratio:¶
  • ( Avg_Open_To_Buy / Credit_Limit ) + Avg_Utilization_Ratio = 1

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

We will perform univariate analysis on all the variables and provide observations on their distributions. (histograms, boxplots, countplot etc).

We will also perform bi-variate analysis to explore relationships between the important variables in the dataset (ie explore relations between numerical variables as well as relations between numerical and categorical variables; inclduing ofcourse the relationships of all the 'x' variables with the target 'y' variable ie 'Attrition_Flag')

Questions:

  1. How is the total transaction amount distributed?
  2. What is the distribution of the level of education of customers?
  3. What is the distribution of the level of income of customers?
  4. How does the change in transaction amount between Q4 and Q1 (total_ct_change_Q4_Q1) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?
  5. How does the number of months a customer was inactive in the last 12 months (Months_Inactive_12_mon) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?
  6. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with each other?

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(8, 5), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=10,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage
    # Get the current figure and change its sizes
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_figwidth(3)
    fig.set_figheight(5)
    plt.tight_layout()

    plt.show()  # show the plot
    #@

# function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True,normalize='index')#.sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 100)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_figwidth(1.5)
    fig.set_figheight(3)
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(8, 5))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],

Model Building¶

We will use the following approach to arrive at the best model:

  • 1) Build 5 models including Decision Tree, Randomforest, BaggingClassifier, AdaBoosting classifier and GradientBoost.
  • 2) Train each of these 5 models with 3 varieties of training samples - original sampled data, under-sampled data and over-sampled data
  • 3) Compare the 15 models for their performance wrt the selected metric of interest and pick the top 3 best performing models as demonstrated on the validation set
  • 4) Tune (using RandomizedSearchCV) the top 3 best performing models using the train-set and re-test their performance on the validation set.
  • 5) Select the best performing model obtained from point #4 above and use it to test its performance on the test set.

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  • Predicting a customer will attrite and the customer doesn't attrite (ie False Positive)
  • Predicting a customer will not attrite and the customer attrites (ie False Negative)

Predicting a customer will not attrite but he attrites is more critical i.e. losing on a valuable customer or asset. We will therefore need to reduce False Negatives. Bank would want Recall to be maximized given greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus while building the model will be on increasing Recall or minimizing the false negatives.

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train and test set so we can call it while evaluating models.

In [ ]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1

        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Model Building with original data¶

In [ ]:
models = []  # Empty list to store all the models
models_train_scores = {} # to capture training scores
models_val_scores = {} # to capture valiation scores
performance_difference = {} # to capture the performance diff btw train set and val set

# Appending models into the list
models.append(("Dtree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced')))
models.append(("Bagging", BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced'), random_state=1)))
models.append(("Random forest", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced')))
models.append(("Adaboost", AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("GradientBoosting", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1)))

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    #nTraining Performance:
    scores_train = recall_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train))
    models_train_scores[name] = scores_train # save all the train scores

    #Validation Performance:
    scores_val = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    models_val_scores[name] = scores_val # save all the val scores

    #Performance difference:
    performance_difference[name] = scores_train - scores_val

# Get all the scores in a single neat dataframe for comparison
models_train_scores_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(models_train_scores, orient='index',columns=['Training Performance'])
models_val_scores_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(models_val_scores, orient='index',columns=['Validation Performance'])
models_per_diff_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(performance_difference, orient='index',columns=['Performance Difference'])

All_scores_Original_data = pd.concat([models_train_scores_df,models_val_scores_df,models_per_diff_df],axis=1)

# Create a fresh new set of models and use the oversampled train set to train. Ese the val set then to test the newly trained models that were using the oversampled training set
models = []  # Empty list to store all the models
models_train_scores = {} # capture training scores
models_val_scores = {} # capture valiation scores
performance_difference = {} # capture the performance diff btw train set and val set

# Appending models into the list
models.append(("Dtree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced')))
models.append(("Bagging", BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced'), random_state=1)))
models.append(("Random forest", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight='balanced')))
models.append(("Adaboost", AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("GradientBoosting", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1)))

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train_over, y_train_over)

    #nTraining Performance:
    scores_train = recall_score(y_train_over, model.predict(X_train_over))
    models_train_scores[name] = scores_train # save all the train scores

    #Validation Performance:
    scores_val = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    models_val_scores[name] = scores_val # save all the val scores

    #Performance difference:
    performance_difference[name] = scores_train - scores_val

# Get all the scores in a single neat dataframe for comparison
models_train_scores_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(models_train_scores, orient='index',columns=['Training Performance'])
models_val_scores_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(models_val_scores, orient='index',columns=['Validation Performance'])
models_per_diff_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(performance_difference, orient='index',columns=['Performance Difference'])

All_scores_over_data = pd.concat([models_train_scores_df,models_val_scores_df,models_per_diff_df],axis=1)

HyperparameterTuning¶

Note

  1. Sample parameter grids as were provided for GBM, Adaboost and bagging models were played around with to arrive at the best hyperparameters for tuning. These sample grids are expected to provide a balance between model performance improvement and execution time. It is noted that if the parameter grid is extended to improve the model performance further, the execution time will increase.

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

Following are some of the key business insights and conclusions for close review and consideration by the bank:

  1. The bank should closely monitor the (12 month rolling) Total_Trans_Amt on an ongoing basis (and to that extent, the Total_Trans_Ct as well give it is highly correlated to the Total_Trans_Amt). It is the most important feature for attrition prediction and therefore provides an early warning signal of a customer attritting. Lower the value, higher the likelihood of a customer attritting - 75% of attritted customers had Total_Trans_amt below ~2500 dollars compared to 25% existing customers with Total_Trans_Amt below ~2500 dollars. Similarly, Attritted customers showed much lower Total_Trans_count. 75% of them had Total_Trans_ct below 50 compared to 25% existing customers having Trans_ct below 50.

  2. Similarly, the bank should pay close attention to the revolving balance. Lower the revolving balance, higher the risk of customer attrition. Attritted customers show relatively a much lower revolving credit balance compared to existing customers.

  3. Also, lower the Total_Ct_Change_Q4_Q1, higher is the risk of customer attrition. The bank should send promotional offers in Q1 to customer who showed marked reduction in the number of transaction in Q1 vs Q4.

  4. Similarly, lower the no. of products held by a customer (ie measured as Relationship_Count), higher is the chance of customer attrition. There is half a chance that a customer will attrite if he/she had less than 3 products of the bank.

  5. Moreover, customer inactivity for more than 2 months also indicated risk of losing a customer. 50% plus of Attritted customers showed inactivity of more than 2 months.

  6. We also noted that higher the no. of contacts by the customer, higher is the risk of customer attrition. Almost all customers who have had more than 4 contact counts in the last 12 months with the bank, had attritted. The bank should double down on processes in place to promptly and proactively revert to customers especially those who have tried to contact the bank more than 4 times in the last 12 months.

  7. Wrt Demographics:

    • Customer attrition in the Doctorate sub-segment seems to stand out of the pack in the education qualification category. The bank should pay special attention to such customers with doctorate degree specially customers with doctorate degree coupled with other risk factors such as low total_trans_amt, low revolving balance etc.
    • Customer attrition seems to be fairly agnostic of customer age, gender, marital status aswell as income category

  8. The bank should also monitor the average utilization ratio of customers. There is a stark drop in Avg_Utilization_Ratio in attrited customers vs existing customers and therefore provides a cue on the risk of attrition.

In conclusion, demographics except education qualification does not seem to play a critical role in influencing customer attrition and therefore there is pressing need for the bank to focus on services rendered across all customer demographics. Early warning flags such as Total_Trans_Amt, Revolving credit, customer inactivity for more than 2 months and reduced utilization ratios should be closely monitored to remediate ahead of time. Such customers should be reached out to, proactively, and feedback on their experiences of the services taken. Further, the bank should consider making targetted marketing and promotional offers to such customers including selling atleast 3 or more other products of the bank to improve their 'stickiness'. Finally, the prediction model should be deployed on expediated basis and predictions be used to make targetted margeting campaigns to 'risky' customers aswell. (The model prediction-output should be monitored routinely and feature adjustments should made on an on going basis as the banks evolves its business including in managing its customers better based on the insights and recommendations provided above.)
